[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:KQJT.KJ9754.A.95 A95.QT2.KQT63.K8 642.83.974.JT743 873.A6.J852.AQ62"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1H 1NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "ec36dfa0f7a49a86d39871ccc92f6aedd45f7e91c2215252e594054734e0f363"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{You should not make a takeout double with three cards in their suit. A 2\D overcall would be a reasonable choice. But with 15 points, balanced, and a stopper in \Hs a 1NT overcall is probably better.

Partner bids 3NT.

North plays 3NT. As expected, East leads his partner's \H suit.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 1/2 : \D = 0 : \C = 3 :: Total = 5/6

You need at least 4 \D winners.

If you play low from dummy on the \H lead West can win the \HK but this will give you an extra \H stopper. He could drive out dummy's \HA at trick 2, but you would then establish \Ds and make an overtrick! 

But who said West would play another \H after winning the \HK? What if he wins the \HK and switches to \Ss? They might then win 3 \S tricks to go with their \HK and \DA. 

Instead you should grab the first trick with dummy's \HA and start playing \Ds. West will take the \DA but you still have the \SA and \HQ as stoppers.

Just look at West's hand. If you duck the \HA it will be crystal clear to him that he can defeat the contract by winning the \HK and then switching to the \SK.

Don't give him the chance.}
[Play "W"]H8

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "W:K63.AT5.A762.A75 AQJ974..KQJ3.J83 85.QJ97642.9.K94 T2.K83.T854.QT62"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1NT 2S 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "ffc5f566bf2cfff6e1724bb5cb8e2bfb5a69eaa44f7e30d3781a186fe19c78af"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{You would really like to have a transfer bid in this situation, to make West bid \Hs.

But you don't have one, so you just bid 4\H yourself.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \ST. You play low in dummy and South holds the trick. He continues the suit and North takes the \SQ and then plays the \SA.

Loser List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

You've already lost the 2 \Ss. If South has the \HK you might avoid a loser there. You don't have a winner on which to discard the \C loser. 

If North has the \HK it will have to be a singleton to help you, so it is more logical to play South for the \HK.  But if South does have the \HK it will do you no good to ruff North's \SA, South will over-ruff and you would still have that \C loser. 

So do it this way instead. Discard the \C loser on North's \SA! Another \S from North won't hurt you since dummy would be able to over-ruff South. Whatever North plays you can win, then finesse South out of his \HK.

It was said earlier that you didn't have a winner on which you could discard the \C loser.

That was true, so instead you were able to discard it on a loser! }
[Play "W"]ST

